This paper deals with the identification of reasoning patterns in games, which is a problem in artificial intelligence (AI) and game theory (GT). Therefore, cs.AI and cs.GT are the most likely sub-categories. The algorithm presented in the paper involves examining the graph structure of a Multi-Agent Influence Diagram (MAID), which is a type of probabilistic graphical model. This suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of cs.LG (machine learning) and cs.SI (social and information networks). Finally, the algorithm's potential for exponential time savings implies that it may have implications for computational complexity theory, which falls under the sub-category of cs.DS (data structures and algorithms).
